thamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–1270":"–1270","1169–1234":"1169–1234","1190–1231":"1190–1231","1224–1304":"1224–1304","1147–1204":"1147–1204","–Female":"Deceased","1190":"1190","Aft 1204":"after 1204","1231":"1231","1270":"1270","1304":"1304","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1204":"1204","1224":"1224","Abt 1234":"about 1234","1147":"1147","1169":"1169","1234":"1234","before 1192":"before 1192","31 August 1231":"31 August 1231","Duston, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Duston, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Ebbesbourne Wake, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ebbesbourne Wake, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Bourne, Lincolnshire, England":"Bourne, Lincolnshire, England","Duston, Northamptonshire, England":"Duston, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wake","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","occupational name for ‘(man of) the watch’, from Middle English <i>wak</i>, <i>wake</i> ‘wake, vigil, watch, period of guard duty’ (Old English <i>wacu</i>, Old Norse <i>vaka</i>). It alternates with the synonymous Middle English <i>wache</i> (Old English <i>wacce</i>), hence the variant <b>Watch</b>. The surname was also interchangeable with   Waite   (the equivalent Old French term) which, like <i>Wake</i>, was sometimes translated as Latin <i>vigil</i> ‘(one who is) watchful, alert’. Compare the synonymous   Vail  . When the bearers had high social status, the surname probably denoted an officer with responsibility for the security of a castle, town, or royal person. Compare   Wakeman  .","variant of   Wack  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vail","meanings":["English: occupational name from Old French <i>de la veille</i> ‘of the watch, watchman’, with loss of <i>de</i>; compare   Wake  . There has been some confusion with the topographic name   Vale   and the nickname   Veal  .","Scottish: shortened and altered form of   McPhail  , Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Phàil</b> ‘son of Paul’.","Irish: variant of   Veale  ."]},{"name":"Waite","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name for a watchman, either in a town or castle, from Anglo-Norman French <i>waite</i> ‘watchman, member of the watch’ (of ancient Germanic origin; compare   Wachter  ). In the Middle Ages the town waits typically combined the functions of watchmen and musicians through being trumpeters or pipers. There may also have been some late confusion with   White   or   Wheat  ."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Maria</i> via Old Welsh <i>Meir</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":63,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":72,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":107,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and Franc